          "anchor" : "Laws-of-Surds",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Laws of Surds",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\sqrt{a\\times b} = \\sqrt{a} \\times \\sqrt{b}",
            "",
            "\\sqrt{\\dfrac{a}{b}} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{a}}{\\sqrt{b}}",
            "",
            "\\sqrt{a} \\times \\sqrt{a} = a",
            "",
            "a + b\\sqrt{c} = d\\sqrt{c} \\quad \\Rightarrow \\quad a = d \\text{ and } b = c"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Conjugate-Surds",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Conjugate Surds",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Conjugate surds are surds of the form",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "a\\sqrt{m} + b\\sqrt{n}",
            "",
            "\\text{or, when } m = 1,",
            "",
            "a + b\\sqrt{n}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where a and b rational, and m and n are positive integers.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "You can solve equations with conjugate surds by comparing their coefficients. For example, in",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "a + b \\sqrt{k}",
            "\\text{and}",
            "c + d \\sqrt{k}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "if a, b, c, and d are rational, then a = c and b = d.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Rationalisation",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Rationalisation",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "(\\sqrt{m} + \\sqrt{n}) (\\sqrt{m}-\\sqrt{n}) = (m-n)"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Turn irrational to rational üëç",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "A fully simplified surd fraction is simplified when its denominator is NOT a surd.  Multiply the surd in",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "the denominator by its conjugate surd to rationalise. For example,",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\times \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Sometimes, the denominator may be a conjugate surd instead of just a surd. In such cases, we can make use of",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "the quadratic property of ‚Äúdifference of squares‚Äù to simplify the denominator. For example,",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\frac{6}{4\\sqrt{2} - \\sqrt{3}}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{6}{4\\sqrt{2} - \\sqrt{3}} \\times \\frac{4\\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{3}}{4\\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{3}}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{6(4\\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{3})}{4^2 \\times 2 - 3}",
            "",
            "= \\frac{24\\sqrt{2} + 6\\sqrt{3}}{29}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Simplifying-surds",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Simplifying surds",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Surds can be expressed in simplest form by removing the square factors from the radicand. For example,",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "\\sqrt{72} = \\sqrt{2 * 2 * 2 * 3 * 3} = \\sqrt{2^2 * 3^2 * 2} = 2*3\\sqrt{2} = 6\\sqrt{2}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
